          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="578" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835056?width=860&amp;height=578" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆被驱逐。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：issouf sanogo/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133127"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">伯努瓦·福肯 (Benoit Faucon)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-m-phillips" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·M·菲利普斯 (Michael M. Phillips)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 11:42 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-threaten-to-charge-ousted-president-with-treason-dd3cae01"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尼日尔新军政府周一表示，将以叛国罪和危害西非国家安全的罪名起诉被罢黜的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆。</p><p>在官方媒体上发表的一份声明中，军政府表示，它还有足够的证据来指控巴祖姆的未透露姓名的“本地和外国同谋”。巴祖姆是一位民选亲西方领导人，自从在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一场不流血的起义</a>中被推翻以来，他一直被关押在自己的官邸中7 月 26 日，总统卫兵陪同。</p><p>这一声明加剧了尼日尔和以地区强国尼日利亚为首的其他西非国家之间的言论，这些国家实施了经济制裁，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/african-force-to-reverse-niger-coup-could-take-months-95962335?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁要使用军事力量</a>扭转上个月的政变。尼日尔的两个邻国马里和布基纳法索的军政府表示，他们可能会保卫军政府，这在这个世界上最贫穷的地区引发了地区战争的担忧。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="390" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835057?width=700&amp;height=390" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥马尔·查尼 (Omar Tchiani)，政变后政府领导人。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一名西非陆军高级指挥官表示，军政府威胁起诉巴祖姆很可能是为了在西非国家经济共同体（西非经共体）内与批评者进行谈判之前巩固自己的地位。</p><p>巴祖姆领导的尼日尔民主与社会主义党表示，叛国罪的审判只能在该国宪法法院进行，因此只有恢复法治才能进行。该党声明称：“煽动性士兵必须返回各自的军营，让共和国机构，包括他们默认的机构，履行职责。”</p><p>美国、法国和其他西方国家对尼日尔事态的转变感到震惊，在巴祖姆的领导下，尼日尔一直是打击基地组织、伊斯兰国和博科圣地武装分子的亲密盟友，这些武装分子在西非发动了数千次袭击。</p><p>美国在尼日尔拥有两个无人机基地和 1,100 名士兵，这次政变可能会颠覆其训练尼日尔特种部队（被认为是西非最有效的部队之一）打击伊斯兰极端分子的战略。法国在其前殖民地驻有约 1,500 名士兵，在政变之前，法国既执行了自己的行动，也执行了与尼日尔军队的联合行动。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3378CE7F-EFF6-4894-9BB5-E959728F6C12&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-coup-leaders-threaten-to-charge-ousted-president-with-treason-dd3cae01&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尼日尔政变背后的军政府表示，他们计划在上个月软禁被罢免的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆后，以叛国罪起诉他。军政府无视国际社会要求巴祖姆复职的呼声。照片：Ludovic Marin/新闻中心<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>周一，基地组织附属武装分子声称在上周的一次袭击中杀死了六名尼日尔士兵。该武装组织张贴了缴获的武器和装甲车的照片。</p><p>巴祖姆的副参谋长达乌达·塔库巴约克(Daouda Takoubayoke)将这次袭击归咎于军政府，他说军政府将此前专注于打击武装分子的尼日尔部队转移到了保护首都的政变策划者。塔库巴约克表示，周一的袭击是政变以来对政府军事阵地的第六次此类袭击。</p><p> “由于担心军事干预将他赶下台，[准将。政变后政府领导人奥马尔·齐亚尼将军打破了反恐斗争的框架，将所有部队转移到尼亚美以保护自己，”塔库巴约克说。</p><p>据尼日利亚官方媒体报道，周末，尼日利亚伊斯兰领导人代表团在尼日尔首都尼亚美会见了奇亚尼，试图找到摆脱危机的和平途径。</p><p>写信给 Benoit Faucon <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（benoit.faucon@wsj.com）</a>和 Michael M. Phillips（ <a href="mailto:Michael.Phillips@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Michael.Phillips@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 15:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-threaten-to-charge-ousted-president-with-treason-dd3cae01</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-threaten-to-charge-ousted-president-with-treason-dd3cae01<author><![CDATA[Benoit FauconMichael M. Phillips]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Argentina’s Dollar Bonds Plummet After Far-Right Outsider Wins Primary Vote]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>哈维尔·米雷 (Javier Milei) 在 10 月总统选举前的初选中获得大部分选票后，央行贬值比索的官方汇率<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132905"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="486" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835118?width=860&amp;height=486" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">极右翼总统候选人哈维尔·米雷周日在布宜诺斯艾利斯的竞选总部发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：alejandro pagni/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132905"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·杜贝</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 11:24（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>周一，阿根廷美元债券暴跌，政府贬值比索官方汇率，一天前，一位极右翼局外人士在十月大选前将自己定位为该<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国的主要希望</a>。</p><p>周一早些时候，该国债券交易价格下跌约 10%。央行将比索的官方汇率贬值，比索贬值超过20%，至1美元兑换350左右。布宜诺斯艾利斯街头的比索黑市汇率略为疲软，约为 600 美元兑换 1 美元。</p><p>哈维尔·米莱 (Javier Milei) 是一位头发蓬乱的 52 岁经济学家，他对他所谓的“政治种姓”表示不满，他在周日的初选中获得的选票比中右翼“共同谋变”联盟和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">执政的庇隆主义运动的</a>得票数还多，引发了骚乱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">候选人</a>，经济部长塞尔吉奥·马萨。</p><p>投资者原本预计“共同谋变”联盟会在投票率较低的投票中表现更好。</p><p>芝加哥威廉·布莱尔投资管理公司的投资组合经理贾里德·卢表示：“低投票率和意外结果导致政治和市场不确定性增加。” “鉴于经济状况不佳，选民似乎要求变革。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FDB4DFD7-9FD4-49A6-9874-2C3D318261D2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fargentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">巴西和阿根廷领导人重新提出了共同货币的想法，以促进贸易并减少该地区对美元的依赖。 《华尔街日报》的萨曼莎·皮尔森解释了为什么它不太可能很快实施。照片：伊芙·哈特利<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>米莱是一位民粹主义新贵，他承诺关闭央行、用美元取代比索并削减支出，她获得了 30% 的选票。</p><p>在决定谁参加 10 月份第一轮总统选举的选举中， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-s-president-names-sergio-massa-as-new-economy-minister-11659044057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">米莱</a>击败了帕特里夏·布尔里奇 (Patricia Bullrich) 和马萨 (Massa)。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-s-president-names-sergio-massa-as-new-economy-minister-11659044057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与极不受欢迎的总统阿尔贝托·费尔南德斯相比，他对商业也更友好</a>。他获得了27.3%的选票。</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé： <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 15:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72<author><![CDATA[Ryan Dubé]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>货币/货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>哈维尔·米雷</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>钱</category><category>货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Musk vs. Zuckerberg Fight May Never Happen, but Italian Cities Are Still Jostling to Host It]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>科技巨头对决的可能性越来越渺茫，但这并没有阻止古代角斗士故乡的狂热兴奋<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835079/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="罗马斗兽场被认为太脆弱，不适合硅谷首席执行官之间的任何斗争。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>罗马斗兽场被认为太脆弱，不适合硅谷首席执行官之间的任何斗争。阿蒂拉诺·加西亚/祖玛出版社<span>阿蒂拉诺·加西亚/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132647"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132647"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-sylvers" itemprop="url" rel="author">埃里克·西尔弗斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 9:43 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-jostling-to-host-it-36957867"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">马克·扎克伯格</a>似乎无法就是否以及何时<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-fight-b71fa4ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">进行笼式比赛达成</a>一致。尽管如此，拥有著名考古场所的意大利城市仍在争相成为一场能够带来大规模全球宣传的活动的舞台。</p><p>上周，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="">特斯拉</a>首席执行官<span class="company-name-type">马斯克</span>在他的社交媒体公司 X（前身为 Twitter）上发布的帖子在意大利各城市引发了热潮。 “相机画面中的一切都是古罗马的，所以根本没有现代的东西。我与意大利总理和文化部长进行了交谈。他们已经就一个史诗般的地点达成了一致。” <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1689963696703848449" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">马斯克写道</a>。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a>母公司 Meta 的首席执行官扎克伯格<a href="https://www.threads.net/@zuck/post/Cv0Kc-yP2Wu" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">周日在竞争对手平台 Threads 上进行了反击</a>，指责马斯克没有认真参加拳击比赛，并对这场比赛表示怀疑。 “埃隆不会确认日期，然后说他需要手术，现在要求在我的后院进行一轮练习。如果埃隆认真对待一次真正的约会和官方活动，他知道如何联系我。”</p><p>这两位科技亿万富翁在六月份表示，他们将互相争斗。从那以后，他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/sports/mark-zuckerberg-elon-musk-fight-cage-match-7b28d9c1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">互相互相嘲讽</a>，但很少透露这场比赛的具体细节。</p><p>马斯克提到的古罗马让许多意大利人认为他指的是罗马城而不是帝国。罗马斗兽场显然是角斗比赛的有力竞争者。</p><p>但在意大利官员称公元 80 年竣工的罗马斗兽场过于脆弱之后，这场看似是世界上最知名的古迹之一的首轮淘汰赛很快就变成了一场混战。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C88AF8C6-9381-4531-8397-8E3466D42127&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmusk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-jostling-to-host-it-36957867&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩 (Joanna Stern) 在人物模型的帮助下分析了为什么这场科技争吵实际上就像过去的硅谷争吵一样。照片插图：Kenny Wassus、Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>意大利文化部长根纳罗·桑朱利亚诺称赞马斯克和扎克伯格的战斗是一场“伟大的事件”，但没有透露可能的地点。该部和意大利总理办公室没有回应置评请求。</p><p>罗马斗兽场退出后，人们的目光转向了马克西穆斯竞技场，这座长椭圆形体育场距离酒店仅几步之遥。</p><p>在古代，马克西穆斯竞技场举办战车比赛，例如好莱坞史诗《宾虚》中描述的比赛。如今，这里偶尔举办摇滚音乐会，有时令当地人懊恼不已。本月早些时候，特拉维斯·斯科特的一场音乐会变得如此喧闹，以至于居民们表示他们以为发生了地震。</p><p>进入舞台右侧：《宾虚》中使用的电影布景，现在是罗马郊区电影主题公园 Cinecittà World 的一部分。该公园的首席执行官称该场地是两全其美，既提供了古老的氛围，又不玷污真正的纪念碑。</p><p>罗马政客们一直在推动<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ostia-a-search-for-the-secrets-of-romes-port-1454089086?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在古罗马港口奥斯蒂亚安蒂卡（Ostia Antica）</a>建造一个相对较小的剧院，距离城市只有很短的火车车程。</p><p>意大利南部的卡拉布里亚地区也提出了自己的观点，地区主席提醒所有人，该地区是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-riace-bronzes-warriors-rescued-from-the-sea-1464385173?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">里亚斯青铜雕像</a>的故乡，这是两尊古老的裸体战士雕像。别介意这两座巨大的雕像是 50 年前从海底打捞出来的，现在存放在博物馆里，它们起源于希腊，比罗马崛起早了几个世纪。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835080?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">埃隆·马斯克上周表示，这场比赛将在意大利举行。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贡萨洛·富恩特斯/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“如果你正在寻找一个史诗般的地方，令人回味和迷人，陶尔米纳就是你的选择，”西西里镇镇长卡特诺·德卢卡 (Cateno De Luca) 在 X.陶尔米纳 (X. Taormina) 上写道，该景点在 HBO 节目中播出后迅速流行起来。 “白莲花”有一个古希腊剧院，可以看到西西里海岸线的全景。</p><p>一份竞争对手的提案来自那不勒斯附近的贝内文托市长，该市有一座罗马剧院，有时被称为罗马斗兽场的双胞胎，另一个提案来自巴西利卡塔南部地区的一个小镇，该镇也有一座罗马剧院。</p><p>庞贝市长提出了在这座被挖掘的古城中使用剧院的理由，这座古城在公元 79 年因维苏威火山爆发而被掩埋。</p><p>维罗纳竞技场是一座保存完好、比罗马斗兽场稍古老的圆形剧场，矗立在不幸恋人罗密欧与朱丽叶的故乡，上演大型歌剧作品。自称“爱之城”的维罗纳市长迄今为止一直保持沉默——也许是因为举办笼斗比赛看起来很尴尬。</p><p>一些意大利人认为，对于一个拥有如此丰富历史和古迹的国家来说，举办亿万富翁之间的打斗是不合适的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835082?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">罗马马克西穆斯竞技场一直在竞选主办这场比赛的机会。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：格雷戈里奥·博吉亚/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835083?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西西里小镇陶尔米纳的古希腊剧院最近人气猛增。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安东尼奥·帕里内洛/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>文化部好斗的副部长维托里奥·斯加尔比(Vittorio Sgarbi)经常介入意大利的文化战争，他表示自己根本不关心这场斗争，也不会观看。他表示，马斯克和扎克伯格可以使用任何潜在的场地，包括罗马斗兽场，只要他们付费。</p><p>斯加尔比说，文化部长桑朱利亚诺已就意大利是否应该主办这次活动征求他的意见。</p><p> “对我来说，这很好，”斯加尔比在接受《晚邮报》采访时回答道。 “他们会给你多少钱？一亿？”</p><p>桑朱利亚诺表示，马斯克和扎克伯格的任何资金都将用于科学研究和升级两家儿科医院。</p><p>斯加尔比表示，他会在这场斗争中支持马斯克，因为特斯拉首席执行官曾在议会演讲中称赞了他。</p><p>另一位反对派议员卡洛·卡伦达 (Carlo Calenda) 在 X 上写道：“我只是觉得令人震惊的是，意大利的文化遗产被提供给了两位想像白痴青少年一样战斗的亿万富翁。”“这不是他们付多少钱的问题。有些东西根本不卖。其中之一就是一个伟大国家的尊严和历史。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835084?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">维罗纳的竞技场是一座保存完好的圆形剧场，比罗马斗兽场稍古老。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Mickael Chavet/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给埃里克·西尔弗斯（Eric Sylvers）： <a href="mailto:eric.sylvers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.sylvers@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 13:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-josdling-to-host-it-36957867</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-josdling-to-host-it-36957867<author><![CDATA[Eric Sylvers]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>马克·扎克伯格</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Canada Tests the Limits of Its Liberal Immigration Strategy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>新移民数量迅速增加，给住房、医疗和交通带来压力<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834831/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="加拿大去年迎来了超过一百万永久和临时移民。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>加拿大去年迎来了超过一百万永久和临时移民。大卫·瑞德/路透社<span>大卫·瑞德/路透社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093529"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093529"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">保罗·维埃拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 9:00（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-tests-the-limits-of-its-liberal-immigration-strategy-bc61e0de"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>渥太华——大量移民使加拿大成为近年来增长第二快的发达国家经济体，仅次于美国，因为它竞相<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-u-s-immigration-system-5f7e866d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">吸引来自世界各地的高技能工人</a>。</p><p>现在，新来者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canadas-immigration-problem-not-enough-homes-for-newcomers-11665144002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开始限制</a>该国吸收他们的能力，使该国增长的一个重要引擎面临风险。</p><p>加拿大统计局称，这个拥有 4000 万人口的国家去年迎来了超过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-stretch-of-canadian-border-bustles-with-migrants-1503efb0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">100 万永久和临时移民</a>。人口涌入导致人口增长 2.7%；增加的105万人几乎相当于美国去年的增幅，而美国的人口是加拿大的八倍多。</p><p>加拿大官员表示，未来两年，他们将把永久新移民的数量增加近三分之一，其中大多数是技术移民，如木匠、计算机科学家和医疗保健工作者，他们符合基于绩效的积分制度。</p><p>该体系由总理贾斯汀·特鲁多 (Justin Trudeau) 政府大力提倡，但于 20 世纪 60 年代首次开发，有助于推动经济增长、吸引企业家并填补技术职位空缺。它得到了加拿大政界的广泛支持，其目标是吸引世界上最优秀和最聪明的人才来到加拿大。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825356?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">加拿大的房价仍然位居世界最高之列。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡罗莱纳安德拉德/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>但新移民的数量增长如此之快，以至于分析师和新移民表示，这给<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-migration-boom-keeps-housing-costs-high-5fc84b7f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">过热的房地产市场</a>火上浇油，给紧张的医疗系统带来压力，并堵塞了不习惯交通拥堵的城市的道路。</p><p>这也促使移民在选择加拿大时三思而后行。 27 岁的卡兰维尔·辛格 (Karanvir Singh) 来自新德里，是一名训练有素的会计师，在都柏林呆了四年后，于去年 11 月获得工作许可证来到多伦多地区。他说，考虑到房价、食品成本和公共交通的低迷，他正在重新考虑。</p><p>辛格说，加拿大“试图尽可能多地让所有移民来这里经营他们的经济，但他们错过了这样一个事实：他们必须建造一个地方，或开发一个地方……这样移民才能在这里生活。”</p><p>达拉斯联邦储备银行编制的数据显示，即使在利率快速大幅上涨之后，该国的房价仍然位居世界最高之列。分析师表示，由于住宅建设跟不上人口增长，加拿大房价比 2020 年水平高出 36%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825693?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">卡兰维尔·辛格 (Karanvir Singh) 是一名训练有素的会计师，去年 11 月抵达多伦多地区，他表示，他正在重新考虑是否留下来。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡兰维尔·辛格</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>约翰·帕萨利斯说：“当我们的政府决定将人口增长速度提高两倍而不考虑每个人的居住地点时，就会发生这种情况。”</p>多伦多房地产经纪公司 Realosophy Realty 总裁。<p></p><p><a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/TD.T">道明银行</a>经济学家在上个月的一份报告中预测，根据当前的人口趋势，满足预期需求所需的住房单位缺口可能会在短短两年内翻一番，达到 50 万套。</p><p> Aurika Tabassum 于 2014 年持学生签证从孟加拉国来到这里，学习人力资源管理。她现在在多伦多结婚，在一家招聘公司工作，并于六月得知加拿大授予她永久居留权。但她和她的丈夫买不起房，他们在多伦多北部租的公寓——两间卧室，这样亲戚从国外来访时可以留下来——花费了他们一半以上的税前工资，她说。</p><p> Tabassum 说，在美国的某些地区，“你可以花 30 万或 40 万美元购买一栋大房子。在这里，你连地下室都买不了。”塔巴苏姆说，她现在警告热衷于在这里定居的孟加拉国朋友和亲戚有关住房成本的问题。</p><p>加拿大以欢迎移民而闻名，并没有经历美国和荷兰等国家最近出现的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/immigration-backlashes-spread-around-the-world-142124bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">强烈抵制</a>。但渥太华 Abacus Data 上个月发布的新民意调查反映出了质疑，61% 的公民表示，政府的计划过于雄心勃勃，因为这对住房和医疗保健产生了负面影响。加拿大医学协会表示，该国的人口与医生比例在 36 个发达经济体中排名第 29 位，而经济合作与发展组织的数据显示，加拿大的医院床位容量是人均最低的国家之一跻身于富裕世界经济体之列。</p><p> “任何时候增加人口，尤其是在医疗资源紧张的环境下，都会产生影响，”加拿大医学协会主席阿利卡·拉方丹博士说。</p><p>以特鲁多为首的加拿大政府官员捍卫了该国的政策。直到上个月末仍担任加拿大移民部长的肖恩·弗雷泽 (Sean Fraser) 表示，来自海外的新工人的增加帮助该国从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-looks-to-immigration-to-boost-economic-recovery-11617105739?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">疫情的经济深渊</a>中恢复过来。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="503" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834830?width=700&amp;height=503" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以总理贾斯汀·特鲁多为首的加拿大政府官员为该国的移民政策辩护。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Adrian Wyld/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>弗雷泽在 6 月份回答问题的电子邮件中表示，新移民发挥了关键作用，“通过新想法、创新和庞大的数量来补充加拿大人才库，以帮助解决严重的劳动力短缺问题”。他说，加拿大正在让熟练的商人和护士更容易在该国定居，并补充说这将有助于缓解住房建设和医疗保健方面的紧缩。</p><p>加拿大央行行长蒂夫·麦克勒姆(Tiff Macklem)上个月在新闻发布会上表示，移民帮助劳动力市场降温，这是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-inflation-cools-in-may-as-gasoline-prices-drop-aa65ec96?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通胀降至</a>央行2%目标的先决条件。该国失业率连续三个月攀升，在 2023 年大部分时间保持在 5.0% 的历史低点后，7 月份达到 5.5%。</p><p> “另一方面，”麦克勒姆说，“这些新移民，他们也是新消费者，他们是新租房者，他们是新购房者，所以他们也增加了需求。”加拿大央行在过去16个月内<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-canada-lifts-interest-rates-warns-path-to-stable-inflation-at-risk-18462fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加息</a>10次，累计加息4.75个百分点，以抑制消费者支出、减缓通胀。</p><p>从历史上看，新移民涌向多伦多、温哥华和蒙特利尔等大城市，但现在他们也在较小的城市和郊区定居。</p><p>根据全国人口普查，加拿大首都渥太华周边地区的总人口在 2016 年至 2021 年间增长了 8.5%，根据加拿大房地产协会的数据，同期房价飙升了 84%。位于多伦多以西 70 英里的基奇纳-滑铁卢-剑桥地区是一个技术和制造中心，人口增长了 10%，达到 575,000 人。 2016-21年期间，房价上涨了一倍多。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825439?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">移民正在大城市以外的小城镇定居，例如位于多伦多以北约 33 英里的布拉德福德西格威廉伯里 (Bradford West Gwillimbury)。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：科尔·伯斯顿/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>随着移民激增，加拿大的人均国内生产总值（经济学家广泛用来衡量一个国家的生活水平）已经下降。国家银行金融上个月表示，加拿大第二季度人均产出有望同比下降1.7%，经济合作与发展组织预测加拿大人均GDP增速可能是最低的之一未来四十年中发达国家经济体的发展。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>美国应该效仿加拿大的移民策略吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>加拿大激进的移民“掩盖了这个国家真正的根本问题，即缺乏商业投资和生产力，”美林前首席北美经济学家、现任罗森博格研究中心负责人戴维·罗森伯格说。他说，这体现在公共交通、道路、医疗保健和住房等各个方面。</p><p>戴尔·雷诺特 (Dale Renout) 是安大略省布兰特福德罗登街浸信会教堂 (Rawdon Street Baptist Church) 的牧师，该教堂的人口比五年前增长了 6.2%。雷诺特表示，他支持移民，但认为现在是加拿大限制新移民数量的时候了，根据他的经验，他试图帮助新移民找到负担得起的租金，但基本上没有成功。他还指出布兰特福德出现了交通拥堵的情况。</p><p> “医院床位没有增加，道路通行能力也没有增加，”雷诺特说。 “我只是不知道新移民要去哪里。”</p><p>写信给保罗·维埃拉 (Paul Vieira)： <a href="mailto:Paul.Vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Paul.Vieira@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-tests-the-limits-of-its-liberal-immigration-strategy-bc61e0de</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-tests-the-limits-of-its-liberal-immigration-strategy-bc61e0de<author><![CDATA[Paul Vieira]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Taiwan Vice President Flashes Defiance Against China During U.S. Stopover]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>赖清德访美期间在纽约发表讲话，北京和华盛顿都在密切关注<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132434"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835016?width=860&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">台湾副总统赖清德周日出席了在曼哈顿宴会厅举行的午餐会。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：台湾总统府/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132434"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joyu-wang" itemprop="url" rel="author">Joyu Wang</a></span> （台北）和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-t-areddy" itemprop="url" rel="author">James T. Areddy</a></span> （纽约）</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 8:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-vice-president-flashes-defiance-against-china-during-u-s-stopover-e3596b74"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>台湾副总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-visit-by-taiwan-vice-president-puts-china-in-a-bind-a275b893?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在纽约短暂停留</a>期间，誓言不会在面对来自中国的威胁时让步，这是美国访问的一部分，北京和华盛顿似乎都保持克制，以<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-taiwan-relations-tensions-explained-11653322751?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">避免重新引发紧张局势</a>。</p><p>赖清德在曼哈顿逗留了大约 24 小时，并于前一天晚上抵达曼哈顿的一个宴会厅，在有 500 多人参加的周日午宴上发表讲话。他在河边遇到了一群喧闹的亲北京抗议者，他进入后就散去。</p><p> “在这个关键时刻，我希望此时此地，我们能够再次重申我们的承诺，无论威权主义对台湾的威胁有多大，我们都不会畏惧和退缩，”赖说。他还感谢美国政府“不屈服于压力”帮助安排他在美国的停留，这间接提到了北京。</p><p>目前在定于一月举行的总统选举中领先的赖智正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-unveils-dates-for-u-s-stops-by-vice-president-despite-chinas-protests-17106008?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">巴拉圭进行为期一周的访问</a>，他计划周二出席该国即将上任的总统圣地亚哥·佩尼亚·帕拉西奥斯的就职典礼。他计划周三在旧金山停留，然后第二天返回台北。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-vice-president-plans-stop-in-the-u-s-at-a-delicate-moment-886e484b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">台湾官员过境</a>美国被正式称为过境，这符合华盛顿数十年来向北京做出的不与这个民主自治岛屿保持正式外交关系的承诺。北京将台湾视为中国的一部分，一再警告美国不要允许黎智英在中途停留时离开机场。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=056CAD44-242B-4B81-BC61-72E5DF1CD69A&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftaiwan-vice-president-flashes-defiance-against-china-during-u-s-stopover-e3596b74&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">几十年来，台湾一直将其东海岸视为在中国入侵时幸存下来的避风港，直到盟友，特别是美国能够到达提供援助。但解放军在该岛东部的活动使这一战略受到质疑。插图：亚当·阿达达<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>周日，黎智英冒险进入纽约后，中国驻纽约领事馆提出抗议，他一度受到一群挥舞旗帜、唱着歌的支持者的欢迎。</p><p> “赖清德是不折不扣的‘台独’分裂分子，”领事馆在一份声明中表示。 “他‘过境’美国的目的是为台湾选举造势，寻求美国对‘台独’的支持”</p><p>赖清德和台湾总统蔡英文都是台湾执政党民进党的党员，但华盛顿和北京都认为赖清德在主张台湾独立方面更加激进——这是中国领导层的红线，中国誓言要控制台湾。必要时使用武力自治岛屿。</p><p>赖表示，如果当选，他将维持与中国的现状。</p><p>尽管如此，美国和台湾官员仍决定低调访问美国，除负责台湾政策的官员外，没有计划与美国官员会面。</p><p>到目前为止，北京方面同样谨慎行事，仅限于口头反应，甚至减少了对台湾附近空域和水域的日常军事入侵。台湾官员和军事分析人士表示，中国可能对采取可能有助于赖以民意调查的挑衅行动持谨慎态度。</p><p>在黎智英出访前几天，中国喷气式战斗机、轰炸机和其他军用飞机每日出动架次超过 30 架次，但台湾国防部表示，周末仅发现 13 架中国战机靠近其领空。报告称，自黎智英周六离开以来，没有人跨越过台湾海峡的中线，这条100英里长的水域将台湾与中国分开。</p><p>在黎智英在周日午餐会上被介绍上台之前，组织者欢迎一些地区政界人士出席活动，其中包括来自纽约、新泽西和宾夕法尼亚州的一些州议员。</p><p>美国在台协会常务董事英格丽德·拉尔森 (Ingrid Larson) 简短致辞，对赖清德表示欢迎。美国在台协会事实上的美国驻台湾大使馆的负责人劳拉·罗森伯格(Laura Rosenberger)通过视频发表讲话，并表示，她期待着黎智英在巴拉圭访问结束后返回美国，并在旧金山欢迎他。</p><p>赖清德利用他的讲话来强化台湾作为对抗中国在亚太地区威权野心的民主堡垒的形象。</p><p>他说：“我们必须勇敢、坚定地走在民主道路上，继续壮大台湾。” “尽管国际形势复杂，但我会以和平为指路明灯。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bf4d14ac-311a-4b61-9cc1-ce0772d8de02.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给 Joyu Wang（ <a href="mailto:joyu.wang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joyu.wang@wsj.com）</a>和 James T. Areddy（ <a href="mailto:James.Areddy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">James.Areddy@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-vice-president-flashes-defiance-against-china-during-us-stopover-e3596b74</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-vice-president-flashes-defiance-against-china-during-us-stopover-e3596b74<author><![CDATA[Joyu WangJames T. Areddy]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>赖清德</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kim Jong Un Calls for Sharp Rise in North Korean Weapons Production]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国和韩国定于下周开始大型军事演习，平壤称之为战争预演<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132369"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835000?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">朝鲜领导人金正恩在参观军工厂时检查一辆装甲车。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：朝中社 VIA KNS/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132369"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">达斯尔·尹</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 7:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-north-korea-weapons-production-e5d0f509"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>首尔——随着美国和韩国加强军事合作以对抗朝鲜，朝鲜领导人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">金正恩</a>呼吁大幅增加武器生产。</p><p>据平壤官方媒体周一报道，这是金正恩<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-spotlights-weapons-amid-u-s-concerns-about-illegal-arms-trade-3375283c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">几周内第二次</a>参观军事工厂，这一次是在周五和周六观察战术导弹、移动发射平台和炮弹的制造。据官方媒体报道，他下令增加为前线部队生产炮弹，“为应对任何时刻的战争做好充分准备”。</p><p>最近几周，朝鲜对其武器生产和军事实力越来越直言不讳。据官方媒体报道，金正恩上周召集军方官员讨论针对韩国的“重大军事行动”，并在会上呼吁“做好战争充分准备”，但该媒体没有详细说明。</p><p>美国和韩国定于下周开始大型军事演习，朝鲜通常将其称为入侵预演。据首尔军方称，今年的一年一度的乙支自由之盾演习<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-south-korea-revive-live-military-drills-after-four-year-hiatus-11661074202?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">——去年以实景演习形式恢复</a>——将是有史以来规模最大的一次，将有数万名士兵以及联合国军司令部成员国参加。</p><p> “这些演习对于应对朝鲜日益增长的军事威胁是绝对必要的，”韩国参谋长联席会议发言人李成俊在周一的新闻发布会上表示。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=901F4C0B-AEB7-4EE0-90AB-3AAD0B945CAA&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fkim-jong-un-north-korea-weapons-production-e5d0f509&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">朝鲜媒体显示，领导人金正恩带着俄罗斯国防部长谢尔盖·绍伊古参观了一个装满武器的大厅，包括导弹和无人机。此次活动正值俄罗斯和中国代表团访问该国庆祝朝鲜战争结束 70 周年。照片：法新社照片/朝中社 VIA KNS<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>朝鲜今年举行了大规模阅兵活动<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korean-parade-puts-missile-production-prowess-on-display-11675937910?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">，纪念其武装部队成立 75 周年</a>，以及结束 1950-53 年朝鲜战争停战协定签署 70 周年，朝鲜将这一天称为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-celebrates-major-holiday-with-special-guests-from-china-and-russia-fc3386fc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">“胜利日”。</a></p><p> 9月9日，纪念共和国成立75周年，将举行民兵阅兵，这可能意味着士兵们走过，而不是武器滚过。</p><p>纪念五周年或十年周年纪念日是夸耀该政权经济和军事成就的机会。但梨花女子大学朝鲜研究教授朴元建表示，制裁和平壤自行关闭边境的影响迫使金正恩强调军队。</p><p> “金正恩越来越频繁地出现在与军事相关的活动和设施中，这表明他没有可以宣传的经济成就，这表明经济正在陷入困境，”朴说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="464" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834999?width=700&amp;height=464" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">朝鲜周一发布了一张未注明日期的照片，显示金正恩正在参观一家军火工厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：朝中社/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>官方媒体照片显示，金正恩身穿白色夹克，驾驶一辆新型通用战斗装甲车，检查正在生产的短程导弹。自<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-north-koreas-kim-end-nuclear-summit-early-11551334804?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">2019 年与美国的谈判破裂</a>以来，朝鲜继续扩大其导弹和核计划。 Pyongyang has fired more than 100 missiles since last year, including a test of a new <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-fires-ballistic-missile-toward-japan-2c728f14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">solid-fuel intercontinental ballistic missile,</a> and showcased new attack drones at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-flaunts-north-koreas-newest-weapons-with-russia-and-china-by-his-side-125399f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">the Victory Day parade</a> last month.</p><p> The Kim regime has justified its military buildup as defensive, as Washington <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">deploys more strategic assets</a> to the Korean Peninsula and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korea-u-s-military-drills-could-use-nuclear-assets-president-yoon-suk-yeol-says-11672669292?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">expands military exercises</a> with South Korea.</p><p> The Ulchi Freedom Shield is a computer-simulated command-post exercise, which was downsized for four years under former South Korean President Moon Jae-in, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korean-president-to-visit-pyongyang-in-bid-to-revive-diplomacy-1537136720?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">sought diplomacy with North Korea</a> . This year&#39;s exercise will include 30 large-scale field-training events, compared with 13 last year. Along with US Army, Air Force and Marine personnel, the US Space Force will also take part in the joint exercises this year, according to the US Forces Korea.</p><p> Earlier this month, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-spotlights-weapons-amid-u-s-concerns-about-illegal-arms-trade-3375283c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">Kim visited five weapons factories</a> , inspecting the production of engines for cruise missiles and drones. When Russian defense minister Sergei Shoigu</p> visited Pyongyang last month to attend the massive Victory Day military parade, Kim gave him a tour of a defense exhibition displaying North Korea&#39;s missiles, launcher trucks and drones.<p></p><p> US officials said Russia was <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-is-again-turning-to-north-korea-to-replenish-ammunition-supplies-d79a5318?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">looking to buy more ammunition</a> from North Korea to replenish its supplies as the war in Ukraine drags on. Moscow and Pyongyang have repeatedly vowed to strengthen cooperation during the war, but denied any weapons deals. The UN Security Council has barred North Korea from testing missiles or selling weapons.</p><p> This Friday, President Biden is scheduled to host South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol and Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida at Camp David, where the three leaders are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-first-camp-david-summit-looks-to-align-allies-facing-china-threat-89626785?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">set to announce their countries will hold joint military exercises annually</a> . The US and its allies are knitting together radar, satellites and weapons systems to counter the North Korean nuclear and missile threat.</p><p> Write to Dasl Yoon at <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 11:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-north-korea-weapons-production-e5d0f509</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-north-korea-weapons-production-e5d0f509<author><![CDATA[Dasl Yoon]]></author><category> Aerospace/Defense</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category> Output/Production</category><category> New Products/Services</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Products/Services</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Kim Jong Un</category><category> output</category><category> production</category><category> new products</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>products</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>aerospace</category><category> defense</category><category> industrial goods </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ozempic Settles the Obesity Debate: It’s Biology Over Willpower]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Weight-loss drugs affect the brain in ways that help researchers understand how the body regulates weight <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834611/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal <span>Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129880"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129880"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/betsy-mckay" itemprop="url" rel="author">Betsy McKay</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 14, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Ozempic and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-drugs-that-are-gaining-on-ozempic-71cdeb51?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">similar drugs</a> are transforming the world&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-weight-loss-body-positivity-marketing-6e918f8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">understanding of obesity</a> . It isn&#39;t so much about willpower <strong>:</strong> It&#39;s about biology.</p><p> The success of the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-diabetes-drug-weight-loss-c0e03c25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">powerful new class</a> of diabetes and weight-loss drugs shows how important chemistry is to determining a person&#39;s weight. The brain is the body&#39;s chief chemist, regulating appetite and making it difficult for many people to shed pounds and keep them off. The brain determines how much fat it wants people to carry, according to years of research <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mounjaro-eli-lilly-weight-loss-new-study-5f7661cc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bolstered by the new drugs</a> .</p><p> The amount is like a setting on a dial, or what many researchers call a “set point” or “defended fat mass.” The brain maintains the dial setting or set point by regulating how much a person eats. Ozempic, its sister drug Wegovy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-mounjaro-weight-loss-drug-wegovy-eli-lilly-66f2906?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">and another, Mounjaro</a> , lower the dial setting, or set point, in effect by acting on the brain to reduce hunger and make a person feel full sooner, some obesity researchers say <strong>.</strong></p><p> The new set point lasts as long as a patient <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-stop-weight-loss-ea925ae1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is on the drug</a> , they say. Patients who ate a lot before they started taking one of the drugs <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-weight-loss-drugs-strains-relationships-327ab217?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">feel less hungry</a> and fill up more quickly—sometimes after one slice of pizza when they once ate the whole pie.</p><p> “This is not about willpower or personal choice,” said Dr. Florencia Halperin, an endocrinologist and chief medical officer of Form, a virtual medical weight-loss clinic. “This is about your brain driving behaviors.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=35CD7B9E-3215-4417-9DEE-8FF9D9BBEDC9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fweight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Diabetes drugs could become an effective way to treat behavioral issues and addiction. WSJ&#39;s Daniela Hernandez breaks down the science of how they work and how they could change psychiatry forever. Photo illustration: Elizabeth Smelov<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The drugs and their insights into biology have arrived at a precarious point in the losing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pediatricians-recommend-weight-loss-drugs-for-obese-children-11673213563?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">battle against obesity</a> . Although Americans spend billions of dollars a year to shed pounds, growing numbers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/more-states-show-prevalence-of-obesity-cdc-finds-11631734589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are overweight</a> . Nearly 42% of US adults have obesity, according to the <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a> latest <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">government statistics</a> , up from 31% in 1999. So do <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/childhood.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">one in five</a> <strong>&nbsp;</strong> children.</p><p> People with obesity are more likely to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-decades-of-progress-america-backslides-on-heart-disease-11561129106?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">develop heart disease</a> , stroke and diabetes. Treating them is driving more than $170 billion in <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0247307#pone.0247307.ref002" target="_blank" class="icon none">yearly costs</a> . Wegovy has been shown to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wegovy-weight-loss-drug-heart-attack-stroke-570f435e?mod=hp_lead_pos6&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reduce cardiovascular risk</a> , and Mounjaro is being studied for additional health benefits.</p><p> The new medicines have put some long-held assumptions about weight and health on the chopping block. “What these drugs have proven is that patients are right: It&#39;s not their fault,” said Dr. Louis Aronne, an obesity treatment specialist and professor of metabolic research at Weill Cornell Medical College.</p><p> He and many other specialists who study obesity or prescribe the new drugs have advised or conducted studies for the companies making them. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834335?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An injection pen for Ozempic, one of the new class of drugs upending long-held assumptions about body weight.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jaap Arriens/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Jon Weisman</p> was about 300 pounds, prediabetic and at risk of heart disease when he sought help losing weight in 2020. The 46-year-old, who works in mortgage banking and real estate in Boston, had tried restricting food but always then felt hungrier. “I&#39;m not wired for 2,000 calories a day,” he said. “I&#39;m probably wired for 4,000.”<p></p><p> He went back on an earlier-generation weight-loss drug, Saxenda, that he had tried before. He lost about 30 pounds, but then hit a plateau.</p><p> In September 2021 he conferred with Dr. Halperin, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-you-cant-find-wegovy-the-weight-loss-drug-11670108199?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">prescribed Wegovy.</a> His hunger quickly abated. He no longer craved onion rings, mac and cheese and other heavy foods that he once chowed down in marathon dinners with friends, now preferring greens and proteins. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834317?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jon Weisman is taking Wegovy.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jon Weisman</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> He reached his goal weight of 180 pounds a couple of months ago, and is staying on the drug, which he sometimes has to call around to a few pharmacies to find. “This is something I am going to have to have treated for the rest of my life,” he said. He is off the two blood pressure medications he was on, has switched to a low dose of a cholesterol-lowering drug and is no longer prediabetic. He eats a little more now, to maintain rather than lose weight.</p><p> The obesity epidemic is a product of forces, old and new, that have collided in people like Weisman: human biology shaped over millennia of struggle to find sustenance; lives that are largely lived sitting down; and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cake-could-be-the-secret-to-teaching-kids-about-healthy-eating-habits-c4947362?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">abundance of cheap, processed foods</a> .</p><p> Potato chips, soda and other cheap processed foods are a big culprit because they are high in calories, sugar, salt and fat, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-end-of-craving-review-why-you-cant-eat-just-one-11635977800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">they are hard to put down</a> , studies suggest. People who lived for a month in a research facility at the National Institutes of Health ate more and <a href="https://www.cell.com/cell-metabolism/fulltext/S1550-4131(19)30248-7" target="_blank" class="icon none">gained weight</a> on a diet of processed meats and cheeses, tater tots and other processed foods compared with when they were on a diet of vegetables, whole grains, fish and other unprocessed foods, according to a 2019 study.</p><p> For some people, high-calorie foods are especially problematic.</p><p> At least 1,500 genes are linked with weight. Some people are genetically predisposed to gain weight, depending on the combinations of variants in those genes, said Ruth Loos, a professor focused on the genetics of obesity at the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVO" class="company-name">Novo Nordisk</a> Foundation Center for Metabolic Research at the University of Copenhagen and at the Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai. These genes often act in the brain.</p><p> Primitive parts of the brain that control breathing, heartbeat and other essential functions collaborate with hormones and the central nervous system to determine how much fat the body wants to have and keep it at the set point. The system has been shaped by thousands of years of humans foraging to survive.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How have Ozempic and other weight-loss drugs changed your understanding of obesity?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The brain sends hunger signals when a person needs fuel to reach or maintain their set point, and signals a sense of fullness when they reach or exceed it. That is why people who lose weight fighting off an illness are ravenous once they recover, or why people <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-ozempic-treat-binge-eating-for-some-the-answer-is-yes-dbdc009f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">feel sick when they overeat</a> . It&#39;s also why people— <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4989512/" target="_blank" class="icon none">like some participants</a> in “The Biggest Loser” TV series—tend to regain weight even after they try to lose it, according to research.</p><p> The set point isn&#39;t set: It changes naturally throughout a person&#39;s lifetime. Babies lose body fat. Women gain weight during pregnancy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-if-we-could-get-rid-of-menopause-7adbc4e0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">and menopause</a> . It can make small changes, with a person gaining or losing a few pounds.</p><p> In a person with obesity, however, the set-point system has gotten out of whack <strong>,</strong> said Dr. Lee Kaplan, director of the Obesity and Metabolism Institute in Boston. The body-fat dial moves to a new higher set point.</p><p> Obesity causes overeating, rather than the other way around, Kaplan said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834339?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Scientists increasingly see the obesity epidemic as arising from the confluence of abundant high-calorie processed foods, sedentary lifestyles and human biology.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Chona Kasinger/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The new drugs are based on a hormone <strong>&nbsp;</strong> called <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-diabetes-drug-weight-loss-c0e03c25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">glucagon-like peptide 1</a> , or GLP-1, secreted primarily in the lining of the gut in response to food, and in the brain. Drug hunters were initially interested in GLP-1 because it plays an important role in regulating blood sugar. The first GLP-1 drugs were approved to treat diabetes in 2005.</p><p> Wegovy is the only GLP-1 drug approved by the Food and Drug Administration <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/employers-cut-off-access-to-weight-loss-drugs-for-workers-cb277a44?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">as an anti-obesity treatment</a> , while Ozempic, with a lower dose of the same active ingredient, semaglutide, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-runs-low-for-diabetes-patients-as-weight-loss-use-surges-286bf21a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is approved for diabetes</a> . The FDA is expected soon to approve Mounjaro for weight loss. Mounjaro, already cleared to treat Type 2 diabetes, mimics the action of a hormone called GIP in addition to GLP-1.</p><p> The medications essentially lower the set point by activating GLP-1 receptors in the hypothalamus and brain stem that regulate weight and appetite, said Randy Seeley, a professor of surgery and director of the Michigan Nutrition Obesity Research Center at the University of Michigan. The drugs also indirectly reach neurons in parts of the brain involved in reward sensations and impulse control.</p><p> “We are in a constant search to identify the most critical neurons that respond to these drugs,” he said.</p><p> Once a patient reaches a new set point, some of their appetite returns—they are no longer feeling overfed—but the medications keep them at their new level, Seeley said. If a patient stops taking the medication, the new set point no longer holds, which is why people regain weight, he said.</p><p> The set point concept is hard to prove definitively, some researchers say. The makers of the drugs, Novo Nordisk and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LLY" class="">Eli Lilly</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> say their drugs reduce hunger and increase satiety while a person takes them.</p><p> Researchers want to figure out what makes the set point go way up for some people, leading to obesity, Kaplan said: “For the moment, it&#39;s a black box.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/11004b12-051f-4044-aa8a-823e293913dd.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Betsy McKay at <a href="mailto:betsy.mckay@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">betsy.mckay@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173<author><![CDATA[Betsy McKay]]></author><category> wsjhealth</category><category>药品</category><category>Scientific Research Services</category><category> Healthcare/Life Sciences</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>Specialized Drugs/Medications</category><category> Hormone Products</category><category> Diabetes Drugs</category><category> Medical Research Services</category><category> Drug Discovery/Development</category><category> Healthcare Support Services</category><category> Diagnostic/Medical Research Services</category><category> Biology</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Chemistry</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>Obesity</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> biology</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>chemistry</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>obesity</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>社会问题</category><category>pharmaceuticals</category><category> scientific research services</category><category> healthcare</category><category> life sciences</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>specialized drugs</category><category> medications</category><category> hormone products</category><category> diabetes drugs</category><category> medical research services</category><category> drug discovery</category><category> development</category><category> healthcare support services</category><category> diagnostic </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Argentines Back Far-Right Outsider in Presidential Primary]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Javier Milei has pledged to dissolve central bank, slash spending in a country hammered by inflation, poverty and a moribund economy <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132138"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834985?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Far-right congressman, Javier Milei, capitalized on anger against the political class to win the most votes in Argentina&#39;s primary election.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: alejandro pagni/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132138"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ryan Dubé</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 14, 2023 12:25 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Javier Milei, a far-right outsider in Argentina who has pledged to close ministries and slash spending if elected president, rocked the political establishment Sunday by beating out conservatives and the ruling Peronist coalition in a primary vote ahead of October&#39;s elections.</p><p> With more than 80% of ballots counted, Milei, a congressman who says he would dollarize Argentina&#39;s economy and dissolve the central bank, had 31% of the vote as he capitalized on anger against the political class. The country of 46 million people is living through its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-s-president-names-sergio-massa-as-new-economy-minister-11659044057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">worst economic crisis</a> in a generation, hobbled by inflation at 116%. Four of every 10 Argentines live in poverty, struggling to survive with a currency that is increasingly worthless.</p><p> “If we don&#39;t change today, the only destiny will be to turn into the biggest slum in the world,” Milei said to his supporters in his closing campaign rally on Aug. 7. “I don&#39;t want your vote so you give me the power, but to give you back your freedom so you can be the architects of your own destiny and we can end this state that makes us poor, with inflation and crime, and put the country on the path to growth.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Milei, a long-haired, 52-year-old economist, rails against the ruling class in interviews and darts across the stage in speeches, promising to wash away both institutions and the politicians who are in office. He calls himself an anarcho-capitalist who would slash spending, cut taxes and end a bloated state.</p><p> “If the central bank emits money, it causes damage, if they move to control money, they cause damage,” he told The Wall Street Journal in an interview last year. “The only way for it not to cause damage is to do nothing, so why would I want them? I&#39;d close it because it&#39;s a risk if it&#39;s operating.”</p><p> Milei stunned pollsters by receiving more votes than the traditional political coalitions on the left and right that have governed in recent years and failed to solve Argentina&#39;s grinding economic problems.</p><p> “There is a generalized sense of disbelief at how well he did,” said Nicolás Saldias, an analyst at the Economist Intelligence Unit who closely tracks Argentina. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834988?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Patricia Bullrich, the center-right coalition candidate, in Buenos Aires on Sunday night.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: AGUSTIN MARCARIAN/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The center-right opposition coalition, Together for Change, received about 28% support. Voters on Sunday selected Patricia Bullrich, a hard-on-crime conservative and former security minister, as the coalition&#39;s candidate in the October election, which serves as the first of two rounds for Argentines to select their next leader.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The ruling Peronists</a> , which have governed Argentina for most of the last 75 years, received 26.69% support. The movement&#39;s candidate will be the economy minister, Sergio Massa, who is considered more centrist and business-friendly than President Alberto Fernández and his vice president, Cristina Kirchner.</p><p></p><p> Milei attracted young voters in the poor barrios around cities such as Buenos Aires who are angered over the lack of jobs and constantly rising prices for food and clothes. Argentina has been unable to tame inflation and stop the peso currency&#39;s fast depreciation after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-imf-reach-deal-to-restructure-bailout-11643379805?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">taking on a $44 billion bailout</a> from the International Monetary Fund in 2018 to avoid a currency crisis.</p><p> “I voted for Milei because, like a majority of Argentines, I am tired of the same so I opted for resounding change,” said Aldana Gómez, an out-of-work office cleaner who calls herself “another of the unemployed majority.”</p><p> “I simply expect a change,” said the 22-year-old Gómez, who lives with her parents in a working-class district outside the capital. She said past governments “had their opportunity and that&#39;s why the country is like it is—a disaster.”</p><p> Asked why he voted for the upstart Milei, César Vargas, a businessman, said: “It&#39;s simple. I&#39;m tired of being defrauded.” He said life has only gotten worse for Argentines in recent years. “I&#39;m hoping for a more just Argentina, in the short-term, like the Chilean or Uruguayan model,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FDB4DFD7-9FD4-49A6-9874-2C3D318261D2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fargentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Brazil&#39;s and Argentina&#39;s leaders have revived the idea of a common currency in a bid to boost trade and reduce the region&#39;s reliance on the US dollar. WSJ&#39;s Samantha Pearson explains why it is unlikely to be implemented anytime soon. Photo: Eve Hartley<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The results Sunday raise uncertainty for Argentina&#39;s political system, which, despite the country&#39;s economic upheaval, had been relatively stable in recent years while its neighbors were battered by social unrest and the rise of political outsiders.</p><p> “Argentina is famous for its economic chaos, but to some degree earned this reputation as having a fairly predictable political system, and that&#39;s no longer the case,” said Benjamin Gedan, an Argentina expert and director of the Latin America program at the Wilson Center.</p><p> Milei was able to tap Argentine anger though polls show that many voters don&#39;t necessarily agree with his policy proposals, which include eliminating public education, creating a market for selling organs, expanding gun ownership and outlawing abortion.</p><p> “The reality is that he channels the almost-universal anger in Argentina right now,” said Gedan. “And it has nothing to do with his policies.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834896?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers in Argentina preparing a polling station. The results of the primary election raise uncertainty for the country&#39;s political system.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Erica Canepa/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Milei faces an uphill battle to become president. His main rival in October appears to be Bullrich, pollsters say. She could attract many conservative and centrist voters in the general election who are concerned that Milei would go too far in overturning the country&#39;s political and economic system, analysts say.</p><p> Milei could also face pushback from investors who would be concerned about his ability to govern and pass overhauls needed to curb public spending and bring inflation down. Milei would likely struggle to pass legislation in an opposition-controlled Congress.</p><p> And on the streets of Buenos Aires and other cities, he would face robust opposition from powerful unions and social movements who are quick to protest.</p><p> “If reforms are not carried out cautiously, you could have enormous social upheaval,” said Gedan. “There is a lot of discomfort among investors about Milei. The reality is that markets don&#39;t like uncertainty.”</p><p> If no candidate wins outright in October, the top two candidates will go to a runoff in November. A second-round vote without a leftist, Peronist candidate, as analysts expect, would be unheard of in Argentina.</p><p> “A runoff between Milei and Bullrich would be unprecedented,” said Sergio Berensztein, a pollster in Buenos Aires. “It&#39;s a vote against inflation, and business as usual.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Silvina Frydlewsky and Juan Forero contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Ryan Dubé at <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:25:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4<author><![CDATA[Ryan Dubé]]></author><category> wsjworld</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Poverty</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Patricia Bullrich</category><category> Javier Milei</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>poverty</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Economic Losers in the New World Order]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Giant subsidies and rising protectionism are upending decades of free trade. Smaller countries, from the UK to Singapore, are getting left behind. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834926/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="印度尼西亚莫罗瓦利工业园附近交通中的工人，该工业园是镍相关产业的中心。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Workers in traffic near Indonesia Morowali Industrial Park, a hub for nickel-related industries. Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images <span>Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ed-ballard" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ed Ballard</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jason Douglas</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-emont" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jon Emont</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 14, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The world&#39;s biggest economies are offering  huge subsidies in a cutthroat race to win the industries of the future. The losers: all the countries that can&#39;t pay up.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-legislation-inflation-reduction-act-small-towns-eb0ce798?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">New tax credits</a> for manufacturing batteries, solar-power equipment and other green technology are drawing a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-biggest-winners-in-americas-climate-law-foreign-companies-c672e09d" target="_blank" class="icon none">flood of capital</a> to the US The European Union is trying to respond with its own <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-to-unveil-clean-tech-plans-in-bid-to-rival-u-s-china-a391ef5a" target="_blank" class="icon none">green-energy</a> support package. Japan has announced plans for $150 billion of borrowing to finance a wave of investment in green technology. All of them are working to become <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-eu-advance-buyers-club-for-ev-battery-minerals-5288287e" target="_blank" class="icon none">less dependent on China</a> , which has a big lead in areas including batteries and the minerals to make them.</p><p> Now, some smaller players are getting left behind. Many are nimble economies that were on the rise during decades of free trade, but are at a disadvantage in a new era of aggressive industrial policy. Industrialized nations such as the UK and Singapore lack the scale to compete against the biggest economic blocs in offering subsidies. Emerging markets such as Indonesia, which had hoped to use <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its natural resources</a> to climb the economic ladder, are also threatened by the shift. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834966?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Intel has been offered $11 billion in subsidies from the German government to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-tsmc-to-build-first-european-chip-plant-in-germany-155e4d8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">build two semiconductor plants</a> , in what Prime Minister Olaf Scholz called the largest foreign direct investment in German history. The pledged government financing is substantially more than the annual budget of Singapore&#39;s Ministry of Trade and Industry.</p><p> “Let me tell you plainly: We cannot afford to outbid the big boys,” deputy Prime Minister Lawrence Wong told supporters at a recent political rally. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834210?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Intel CEO Pat Gelsinger and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz signed an agreement in June for Intel to build two semiconductor plants in Germany.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Chris Emil JanssEn/ddp/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For many tech companies nurtured in the UK, growth lies elsewhere. British battery-technology startup Nexeon, which developed its technology near Oxford, helped by government funding, raised over $200 million last year. Its first commercial factory will be in South Korea, likely followed by a plant in North America.</p><p> “But not the UK, sadly,” said Scott Brown, Nexeon&#39;s chief executive. Nexeon doesn&#39;t see that changing without more government support for the battery industry.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UK/XLON/AMTE" class="">AMTE Power</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> one of the UK&#39;s few homegrown battery manufacturers, has said it may rethink plans to locate a proposed $200-million-plus factory in Scotland given the difference in subsidies on offer in the US and Europe. Arrival, an electric-vehicle startup, said last year it wants to focus its manufacturing in the US instead of the UK, citing the tax breaks.</p><p> The US, which is offering $369 billion in incentives and funding for clean energy as part of the Inflation Reduction Act, is seeing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-green-subsidies-are-attracting-billions-of-dollars-to-red-states-11674488426?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a windfall of foreign investment</a> . German carmaker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/BMW" class="company-name">BMW</a> just broke ground for a new battery plant in South Carolina. South Korean firms <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hyundai-motor-lg-energy-to-build-4-3-bln-battery-jv-in-u-s-97991f73?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Hyundai and</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KR/XKRX/066570" class="company-name">LG</a> announced a $4.3 billion battery plant in Georgia. Panasonic of Japan is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/panasonic-energy-kansas-to-partner-on-4-billion-ev-battery-factory-11657754596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">building a plant in Kansas</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834214?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers prepare the site of a Panasonic EV battery plant near DeSoto, Kan.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Charlie Riedel/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> Unwinding globalization</h3><p> The subsidy race marks a step away from the economic integration that for decades broke down barriers to trade and investment between countries.</p><p> Globalization transformed once-poor countries such as South Korea and Taiwan into high-tech, developed economies, lifting hundreds of millions of people out of poverty. Western consumers got an abundance of affordable consumer goods and a higher standard of living. Technological advances and new management ideas also moved more freely between countries, along with goods and financial resources.</p><p> The model also had steep costs. Once-thriving communities in the US and Western Europe were hollowed out as manufacturing jobs moved to Asia or the former Soviet states. Environmental concerns mushroomed as the global economy consumed more natural resources. Some economies faced destabilizing bouts of capital flight as foreign money flooded in and out.</p><p> Unwinding that global integration—whether for reasons of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/friend-shoring-might-be-bad-for-global-growth-inflation-11654437600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">national security, geopolitical rivalry or supply-chain anxieties</a> —comes with its own problems, economists say. Especially at risk are smaller, developing economies that need access to global markets if they&#39;re to trade their way to greater prosperity.</p><p> “The world as a whole is becoming more inward and turning away from open trade and investment,” said David Loevinger, a former US Treasury official who is managing director for emerging markets at asset manager TCW Group. “Europe, the US and China are in a subsidy competition and the losers in that competition are poorer economies with less fiscal resources.”</p><p> The Western embrace of industrial policy could be especially painful for countries that had hoped to exploit the adoption of green technologies to turbocharge their own economic development. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834220?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A worker at a nickel processing facility operated by Harita in Indonesia. Indonesia hopes to parlay its nickel resources into a world-leading battery industry.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ulet Ifansasti for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Indonesia has ambitions to parlay its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">abundant nickel resources</a> into a world-leading battery industry. But US rules, put in place as part of the IRA, deny subsidies for EV batteries that contain large amounts of minerals from nations that are not American free-trade partners. Indonesia is among them.</p><p> “We have all the natural resources. We have the human resources. And we are a country that&#39;s a democracy,” said</p> Arsjad Rasjid, the head of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry, in an interview. “Please don&#39;t shut us down.”<p></p><h3> The winners</h3><p> As a leader in the subsidy race, the US is experiencing an investment boom. The US took in about 22% of global foreign direct investment last year, making it the world&#39;s top recipient, according to United Nations data. That is slightly lower than the 26% it received in 2021 when global investment bounced back after a lull during the pandemic, but significantly higher than the 13% it got in 2019. Spending on construction related to manufacturing rose 76% in May compared with a year earlier, to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of $194 billion, Census Bureau data show.</p><p> In the UK, Nexeon&#39;s funding underscores the power of the US purse to skew the playing field. As well as the private capital it raised last year, Nexeon received two million pounds, worth about $2.55 million, from a UK government EV-industry fund.</p><p> Weeks later, two US rivals, Sila Nanotechnologies and Group14 Technologies, both got $100 million from the Energy Department under a battery-industry funding program introduced in the 2021 infrastructure law. Like Nexeon, those companies are making silicon-based materials to be used in battery anodes to improve performance. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="458" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834213?width=700&amp;height=458" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers at Wolfspeed, a semiconductor manufacturer in Durham, NC, look on during remarks by US President Joe Biden as part of his Investing in America Tour in March.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Melissa Sue Gerrits/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “The economics of projects in the US are just out of sight,” said Guy Debelle, a former deputy governor of Australia&#39;s central bank and now director of Fortescue Future Industries, the green energy unit of West Australia miner <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/FMG" class="">Fortescue Metals</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> The company is scouting investment opportunities and currently sees the US as the most likely location due to subsidies that could knock up to 60% off a project&#39;s price tag, said Debelle.</p><p> The European Union is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-to-compete-with-u-s-clean-tech-tax-breaks-by-loosening-subsidy-rules-87a7d334?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">preparing its own support package</a> , relaxing limits on subsidies member countries can give industry. By 2030, the EU wants 40% of the key technologies needed for the green transition to be manufactured in the bloc, including solar equipment—a sector currently dominated by China—wind turbines and batteries.</p><p> The US battery production pipeline, which measures capacity from projects in the works, has jumped 67% since the IRA was announced and now matches the size of Europe&#39;s, which grew by 26% over that period, according to estimates by Benchmark Minerals Intelligence, a UK based firm that gathers industry data.</p><h3> The Brexit problem</h3><p> The shift in global trade comes at a particularly awkward time for the UK, which <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-prime-minister-rishi-sunak-tries-free-market-recipe-to-fix-britains-woes-2aa177b8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has been struggling</a> to chart a new course in the global economy after leaving the European Union in 2020, which meant it no longer had easy access to its giant single market.</p><p> Brexit proponents said the UK could strike bilateral trade deals with other countries  and double down on globalization. Since then, momentum for free trade has stalled and now appears to be in retreat.</p><p> “Back during the Brexit vote, nobody had any idea that we&#39;d see a resurgence of industrial policy in the US,” said Gernot Wagner, a climate economist at Columbia Business School.</p><p> Now, the UK government is facing calls from all corners of the country&#39;s economy to respond to the interventionist turn in global economics with its own reinvigorated industrial strategy.</p><p> The UK&#39;s auto sector got a boost recently when the owner of Jaguar Land Rover chose to build a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-cinches-5-billion-ev-battery-plant-as-race-for-green-investments-heats-up-e20b142f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">new EV-battery plant there</a> , but the overall scale of green subsidies lags far behind the US </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834215?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> UK Finance Minister Jeremy Hunt is under pressure to introduce a reinvigorated industrial strategy in response to the interventionist turn in global economics.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tayfun Salci/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Finance Minister Jeremy Hunt has promised to unveil the UK&#39;s response this fall, but has downplayed expectations and said Britain will not “go toe-to-toe with our friends and allies in some distortive global subsidy race.” He said the UK will look to target funding to areas where Britain has a clear competitive advantage.</p><h3> New alliances</h3><p> One solution for countries that can&#39;t compete is to draw rich trade partners closer and benefit from their industrial policies, as Canada and Mexico have done through their free-trade deal with the US, said Chad Bown, a trade expert and former World Bank official at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, a think tank in Washington, DC Indonesia&#39;s government is participating in the American-led Indo-Pacific Economic Framework for Prosperity, an economic pact that it hopes will improve market access for its minerals.</p><p> Last year, Investment Minister Bahlil Lahadalia said Indonesia would seek to form an <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mineral-rich-developing-nations-demand-bigger-piece-of-the-ev-pie-d1421603?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">OPEC-like cartel for nickel</a> , a battery mineral whose production Indonesia dominates, as a response to protectionism by countries that make EVs. An OPEC-modeled organization would coordinate nickel production levels with other major exporters to ensure elevated prices.</p><p> Analysts doubt the plan, in part because other nickel producers don&#39;t want to alienate powerful trading partners such as the US and China. Similar ideas for an OPEC-like organization of lithium producers have been floated by left-wing leaders in Latin America, but haven&#39;t been enacted.</p><p> Indonesia and Zimbabwe have put in place export restrictions on minerals such as nickel, bauxite and lithium, along with requirements that foreign companies build processing facilities in the country as a condition for exporting.</p><p> “I&#39;m not a fan of these policies but they&#39;re clearly very popular,” said Simon Evenett, a professor of international trade and economic development at the University of St. Gallen in Switzerland. “Clearly it will drive up prices and it will increase uncertainty and risk.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834218?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A view of a nickel processing complex operated by Harita in Indonesia. Indonesia and Zimbabwe have put in place export restrictions on nickel and other minerals.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ulet Ifansasti for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —David Luhnow in London and Stuart Condie in Sydney contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Ed Ballard at <a href="mailto:ed.ballard@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ed.ballard@wsj.com</a> , Jason Douglas at <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com</a> and Jon Emont at <a href="mailto:jonathan.emont@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jonathan.emont@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53<author><![CDATA[Ed BallardJason DouglasJon Emont]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> leder</category><category> Machinery</category><category> Batteries</category><category> Industrial Electronics</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category> Renewable Energy Equipment</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Capacity/Facilities</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>Trade/External Payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Sustainable Development/Sustainability</category><category> Trade Barriers/Restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>capacity</category><category> facilities</category><category>政府援助</category><category>补助金</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>trade</category><category> external payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>natural environment</category><category>政治</category><category>sustainable development</category><category> sustainability</category><category> trade barriers</category><category> restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>machinery</category><category> batteries</category><category> industrial electronics</category><category> industrial goods</category><category> renewable energy equipment</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Economic Losers in the New World Order]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Giant subsidies and rising protectionism are upending decades of free trade. Smaller countries, from the UK to Singapore, are getting left behind. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834926/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="印度尼西亚莫罗瓦利工业园附近交通中的工人，该工业园是镍相关产业的中心。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Workers in traffic near Indonesia Morowali Industrial Park, a hub for nickel-related industries. Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images <span>Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ed-ballard" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ed Ballard</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jason Douglas</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-emont" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jon Emont</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 14, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The world&#39;s biggest economies are offering  huge subsidies in a cutthroat race to win the industries of the future. The losers: all the countries that can&#39;t pay up.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-legislation-inflation-reduction-act-small-towns-eb0ce798?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">New tax credits</a> for manufacturing batteries, solar-power equipment and other green technology are drawing a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-biggest-winners-in-americas-climate-law-foreign-companies-c672e09d" target="_blank" class="icon none">flood of capital</a> to the US The European Union is trying to respond with its own <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-to-unveil-clean-tech-plans-in-bid-to-rival-u-s-china-a391ef5a" target="_blank" class="icon none">green-energy</a> support package. Japan has announced plans for $150 billion of borrowing to finance a wave of investment in green technology. All of them are working to become <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-eu-advance-buyers-club-for-ev-battery-minerals-5288287e" target="_blank" class="icon none">less dependent on China</a> , which has a big lead in areas including batteries and the minerals to make them.</p><p> Now, some smaller players are getting left behind. Many are nimble economies that were on the rise during decades of free trade, but are at a disadvantage in a new era of aggressive industrial policy. Industrialized nations such as the UK and Singapore lack the scale to compete against the biggest economic blocs in offering subsidies. Emerging markets such as Indonesia, which had hoped to use <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its natural resources</a> to climb the economic ladder, are also threatened by the shift. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834966?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Intel has been offered $11 billion in subsidies from the German government to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-tsmc-to-build-first-european-chip-plant-in-germany-155e4d8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">build two semiconductor plants</a> , in what Prime Minister Olaf Scholz called the largest foreign direct investment in German history. The pledged government financing is substantially more than the annual budget of Singapore&#39;s Ministry of Trade and Industry.</p><p> “Let me tell you plainly: We cannot afford to outbid the big boys,” deputy Prime Minister Lawrence Wong told supporters at a recent political rally. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834210?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Intel CEO Pat Gelsinger and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz signed an agreement in June for Intel to build two semiconductor plants in Germany.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Chris Emil JanssEn/ddp/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For many tech companies nurtured in the UK, growth lies elsewhere. British battery-technology startup Nexeon, which developed its technology near Oxford, helped by government funding, raised over $200 million last year. Its first commercial factory will be in South Korea, likely followed by a plant in North America.</p><p> “But not the UK, sadly,” said Scott Brown, Nexeon&#39;s chief executive. Nexeon doesn&#39;t see that changing without more government support for the battery industry.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UK/XLON/AMTE" class="">AMTE Power</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> one of the UK&#39;s few homegrown battery manufacturers, has said it may rethink plans to locate a proposed $200-million-plus factory in Scotland given the difference in subsidies on offer in the US and Europe. Arrival, an electric-vehicle startup, said last year it wants to focus its manufacturing in the US instead of the UK, citing the tax breaks.</p><p> The US, which is offering $369 billion in incentives and funding for clean energy as part of the Inflation Reduction Act, is seeing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-green-subsidies-are-attracting-billions-of-dollars-to-red-states-11674488426?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a windfall of foreign investment</a> . German carmaker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/BMW" class="company-name">BMW</a> just broke ground for a new battery plant in South Carolina. South Korean firms <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hyundai-motor-lg-energy-to-build-4-3-bln-battery-jv-in-u-s-97991f73?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Hyundai and</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KR/XKRX/066570" class="company-name">LG</a> announced a $4.3 billion battery plant in Georgia. Panasonic of Japan is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/panasonic-energy-kansas-to-partner-on-4-billion-ev-battery-factory-11657754596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">building a plant in Kansas</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834214?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers prepare the site of a Panasonic EV battery plant near DeSoto, Kan.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Charlie Riedel/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> Unwinding globalization</h3><p> The subsidy race marks a step away from the economic integration that for decades broke down barriers to trade and investment between countries.</p><p> Globalization transformed once-poor countries such as South Korea and Taiwan into high-tech, developed economies, lifting hundreds of millions of people out of poverty. Western consumers got an abundance of affordable consumer goods and a higher standard of living. Technological advances and new management ideas also moved more freely between countries, along with goods and financial resources.</p><p> The model also had steep costs. Once-thriving communities in the US and Western Europe were hollowed out as manufacturing jobs moved to Asia or the former Soviet states. Environmental concerns mushroomed as the global economy consumed more natural resources. Some economies faced destabilizing bouts of capital flight as foreign money flooded in and out.</p><p> Unwinding that global integration—whether for reasons of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/friend-shoring-might-be-bad-for-global-growth-inflation-11654437600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">national security, geopolitical rivalry or supply-chain anxieties</a> —comes with its own problems, economists say. Especially at risk are smaller, developing economies that need access to global markets if they&#39;re to trade their way to greater prosperity.</p><p> “The world as a whole is becoming more inward and turning away from open trade and investment,” said David Loevinger, a former US Treasury official who is managing director for emerging markets at asset manager TCW Group. “Europe, the US and China are in a subsidy competition and the losers in that competition are poorer economies with less fiscal resources.”</p><p> The Western embrace of industrial policy could be especially painful for countries that had hoped to exploit the adoption of green technologies to turbocharge their own economic development. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834220?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A worker at a nickel processing facility operated by Harita in Indonesia. Indonesia hopes to parlay its nickel resources into a world-leading battery industry.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ulet Ifansasti for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Indonesia has ambitions to parlay its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">abundant nickel resources</a> into a world-leading battery industry. But US rules, put in place as part of the IRA, deny subsidies for EV batteries that contain large amounts of minerals from nations that are not American free-trade partners. Indonesia is among them.</p><p> “We have all the natural resources. We have the human resources. And we are a country that&#39;s a democracy,” said</p> Arsjad Rasjid, the head of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry, in an interview. “Please don&#39;t shut us down.”<p></p><h3> The winners</h3><p> As a leader in the subsidy race, the US is experiencing an investment boom. The US took in about 22% of global foreign direct investment last year, making it the world&#39;s top recipient, according to United Nations data. That is slightly lower than the 26% it received in 2021 when global investment bounced back after a lull during the pandemic, but significantly higher than the 13% it got in 2019. Spending on construction related to manufacturing rose 76% in May compared with a year earlier, to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of $194 billion, Census Bureau data show.</p><p> In the UK, Nexeon&#39;s funding underscores the power of the US purse to skew the playing field. As well as the private capital it raised last year, Nexeon received two million pounds, worth about $2.55 million, from a UK government EV-industry fund.</p><p> Weeks later, two US rivals, Sila Nanotechnologies and Group14 Technologies, both got $100 million from the Energy Department under a battery-industry funding program introduced in the 2021 infrastructure law. Like Nexeon, those companies are making silicon-based materials to be used in battery anodes to improve performance. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="458" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834213?width=700&amp;height=458" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers at Wolfspeed, a semiconductor manufacturer in Durham, NC, look on during remarks by US President Joe Biden as part of his Investing in America Tour in March.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Melissa Sue Gerrits/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “The economics of projects in the US are just out of sight,” said Guy Debelle, a former deputy governor of Australia&#39;s central bank and now director of Fortescue Future Industries, the green energy unit of West Australia miner <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/FMG" class="">Fortescue Metals</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> The company is scouting investment opportunities and currently sees the US as the most likely location due to subsidies that could knock up to 60% off a project&#39;s price tag, said Debelle.</p><p> The European Union is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-to-compete-with-u-s-clean-tech-tax-breaks-by-loosening-subsidy-rules-87a7d334?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">preparing its own support package</a> , relaxing limits on subsidies member countries can give industry. By 2030, the EU wants 40% of the key technologies needed for the green transition to be manufactured in the bloc, including solar equipment—a sector currently dominated by China—wind turbines and batteries.</p><p> The US battery production pipeline, which measures capacity from projects in the works, has jumped 67% since the IRA was announced and now matches the size of Europe&#39;s, which grew by 26% over that period, according to estimates by Benchmark Minerals Intelligence, a UK based firm that gathers industry data.</p><h3> The Brexit problem</h3><p> The shift in global trade comes at a particularly awkward time for the UK, which <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-prime-minister-rishi-sunak-tries-free-market-recipe-to-fix-britains-woes-2aa177b8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has been struggling</a> to chart a new course in the global economy after leaving the European Union in 2020, which meant it no longer had easy access to its giant single market.</p><p> Brexit proponents said the UK could strike bilateral trade deals with other countries  and double down on globalization. Since then, momentum for free trade has stalled and now appears to be in retreat.</p><p> “Back during the Brexit vote, nobody had any idea that we&#39;d see a resurgence of industrial policy in the US,” said Gernot Wagner, a climate economist at Columbia Business School.</p><p> Now, the UK government is facing calls from all corners of the country&#39;s economy to respond to the interventionist turn in global economics with its own reinvigorated industrial strategy.</p><p> The UK&#39;s auto sector got a boost recently when the owner of Jaguar Land Rover chose to build a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-cinches-5-billion-ev-battery-plant-as-race-for-green-investments-heats-up-e20b142f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">new EV-battery plant there</a> , but the overall scale of green subsidies lags far behind the US </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834215?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> UK Finance Minister Jeremy Hunt is under pressure to introduce a reinvigorated industrial strategy in response to the interventionist turn in global economics.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tayfun Salci/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Finance Minister Jeremy Hunt has promised to unveil the UK&#39;s response this fall, but has downplayed expectations and said Britain will not “go toe-to-toe with our friends and allies in some distortive global subsidy race.” He said the UK will look to target funding to areas where Britain has a clear competitive advantage.</p><h3> New alliances</h3><p> One solution for countries that can&#39;t compete is to draw rich trade partners closer and benefit from their industrial policies, as Canada and Mexico have done through their free-trade deal with the US, said Chad Bown, a trade expert and former World Bank official at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, a think tank in Washington, DC Indonesia&#39;s government is participating in the American-led Indo-Pacific Economic Framework for Prosperity, an economic pact that it hopes will improve market access for its minerals.</p><p> Last year, Investment Minister Bahlil Lahadalia said Indonesia would seek to form an <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mineral-rich-developing-nations-demand-bigger-piece-of-the-ev-pie-d1421603?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">OPEC-like cartel for nickel</a> , a battery mineral whose production Indonesia dominates, as a response to protectionism by countries that make EVs. An OPEC-modeled organization would coordinate nickel production levels with other major exporters to ensure elevated prices.</p><p> Analysts doubt the plan, in part because other nickel producers don&#39;t want to alienate powerful trading partners such as the US and China. Similar ideas for an OPEC-like organization of lithium producers have been floated by left-wing leaders in Latin America, but haven&#39;t been enacted.</p><p> Indonesia and Zimbabwe have put in place export restrictions on minerals such as nickel, bauxite and lithium, along with requirements that foreign companies build processing facilities in the country as a condition for exporting.</p><p> “I&#39;m not a fan of these policies but they&#39;re clearly very popular,” said Simon Evenett, a professor of international trade and economic development at the University of St. Gallen in Switzerland. “Clearly it will drive up prices and it will increase uncertainty and risk.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834218?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A view of a nickel processing complex operated by Harita in Indonesia. Indonesia and Zimbabwe have put in place export restrictions on nickel and other minerals.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ulet Ifansasti for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —David Luhnow in London and Stuart Condie in Sydney contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Ed Ballard at <a href="mailto:ed.ballard@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ed.ballard@wsj.com</a> , Jason Douglas at <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com</a> and Jon Emont at <a href="mailto:jonathan.emont@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jonathan.emont@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53<author><![CDATA[Ed BallardJason DouglasJon Emont]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> leder</category><category> Machinery</category><category> Batteries</category><category> Industrial Electronics</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category> Renewable Energy Equipment</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Capacity/Facilities</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>Trade/External Payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Sustainable Development/Sustainability</category><category> Trade Barriers/Restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>capacity</category><category> facilities</category><category>政府援助</category><category>补助金</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>trade</category><category> external payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>natural environment</category><category>政治</category><category>sustainable development</category><category> sustainability</category><category> trade barriers</category><category> restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>machinery</category><category> batteries</category><category> industrial electronics</category><category> industrial goods</category><category> renewable energy equipment</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Office Woes and China’s Slowdown Rattle Singapore’s REIT Market]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Some property-trust managers have asked regulators to loosen leverage limits, after their assets fell in value <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833779/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Singapore has drawn dozens of property-trust listings over the past two decades, and has become the biggest Asian market for REITs outside of Japan." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Singapore has drawn dozens of property-trust listings over the past two decades, and has become the biggest Asian market for REITs outside of Japan. Roslan Rahman/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images <span>Roslan Rahman/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127782"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127782"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/weilun-soon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Weilun Soon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 14, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-office-woes-and-chinas-slowdown-rattle-singapores-reit-market-e1367051"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> SINGAPORE—One of Asia&#39;s largest markets for real-estate investment trusts is reeling from America&#39;s office slump and China&#39;s slowing economy.</p><p> Singapore&#39;s $73 billion market for publicly listed real-estate investment trusts was recently shaken after a US office trust run by Manulife said in July that the value of its portfolio <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-18-2023/card/u-s-office-slump-rocks-a-real-estate-investment-trust-in-singapore-E6tW4F1BthU0D66a71kW?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fell 15% in the first half of 2023</a> , causing it to breach a loan covenant. The vehicle and two others that focus on US commercial properties have lost more than two-thirds of their combined market value over the past year.</p><p> Market participants are worried that Manulife US REIT&#39;s woes are the tip of the iceberg. Stock prices of some Singapore-listed REITs that hold commercial properties in China have also fallen this year, as the country&#39;s macroeconomic outlook worsens. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="960" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833994?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SG/XSES/CEDU" class="">Dasin Retail Trust</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> which owns shopping malls in Southern China, said some of its tenants, including the Chinese operator of supermarket chain Carrefour, terminated leases early. It also disclosed in July that its portfolio&#39;s value declined in 2022.</p><p> Some trust managers recently asked the Monetary Authority of Singapore, the country&#39;s top financial regulator, to ease its leverage limits to give them more financial flexibility to negotiate lending terms with banks, according to people familiar with the matter. Singapore REITs generally have to stay within a 45% debt-to-assets ratio.</p><p> A MAS spokesperson said it closely monitors macroeconomic conditions and has regular discussions with the industry. If trusts exceed the leverage limit because their property values declined, that wouldn&#39;t constitute a breach, the spokesperson added.</p><p> Singapore has drawn dozens of property-trust listings over the past two decades, and has become the biggest Asian market for REITs outside of Japan. The vehicles together account for 12% of Singapore&#39;s total stock-market capitalization. The recent declines in US property valuations and stock prices are shaping up to be a test of the market&#39;s resilience. Most China-focused REITs haven&#39;t reported such declines—but analysts say the worry is that the effects of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-stutters-forward-as-growth-concerns-linger-1be8acb2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s sputtering recovery</a> will start to affect occupancy at malls and industrial parks that some of the trusts hold, and their valuations. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="395" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833780?width=700&amp;height=395" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Dasin Retail Trust said some of its tenants, including the Chinese operator of supermarket chain Carrefour, have terminated leases early.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cfoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “There&#39;s a sense of nervousness in the market,” said Vijay Natarajan, a REIT analyst at RHB Bank Singapore. He said a lot of factors have contributed, including rapidly rising interest rates and the pandemic&#39;s effect on overseas properties. These developments have disproportionately affected internationally focused REITs in Singapore, as they tend to have smaller portfolio sizes and are less diversified, he added.</p><p> In the US, many office workers have <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-return-to-the-office-has-stalled-e0af9741?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">resisted going back to the workplace</a> , leading companies to reconsider the amount of office space they need. That is in turn <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hottest-real-estate-play-is-in-your-neighborhood-7e8ff991" target="_blank" class="icon none">sending valuations</a> of office REITs and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stock-prices-of-office-landlords-plummet-as-short-sellers-pile-in-9373fc95" target="_blank" class="icon none">stocks of office landlords lower</a> .</p><p> Manulife US REIT has buildings in or close to major American cities including Los Angeles, Atlanta and Washington, DC</p><p> The trust recently sought independent valuations of its portfolio, and its managers were surprised to learn that it had dropped by $280 million to $1.63 billion.</p><p> The trust&#39;s building, 1750 Pennsylvania Avenue, which is located a block from the White House and counts the US government as its anchor tenant, was valued at $124 million, versus $156 million at the end of 2022.</p><p> Its 11-story office property at 500 Plaza Drive in Secaucus, NJ, for instance, was worth $67 million at the end of June, down 27% from six months earlier, according to valuations provided by a unit of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JLL" class="">Jones Lang LaSalle</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> Just 7 miles away, its office building at 10 Exchange Place in Jersey City was valued at $258 million, down 11% from the end of 2022. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="501" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833782?width=700&amp;height=501" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A view of Exchange Place, Jersey City, NJ</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: timothy a. clary/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The overall loss in value, coupled with a sharp rise in interest rates that increased its borrowing costs, caused the trust to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-18-2023/card/u-s-office-slump-rocks-a-real-estate-investment-trust-in-singapore-E6tW4F1BthU0D66a71kW?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">breach one of its financial covenants</a> . The Manulife US REIT didn&#39;t make a cash distribution for the first half. It said on Monday that its manager made a payment to lower its leverage ratio slightly, and is in talks with lenders about waiving the covenant breach. It may also sell Phipps Tower, an office building in Atlanta, to help bolster its liquidity.</p><p> Shares of the REIT dropped further on Monday. They have lost close to half their value over the past month. The trust is also considering other asset sales to third parties, said Caroline Fong, Manulife US REIT&#39;s deputy chief executive officer.</p><p> Given the sharp drop in valuations in the first half of the year, analysts from DBS said financial support from the trust&#39;s sponsor may be needed to help resolve the problems. That could be in the form of an equity injection or asset sales, they said.</p><p> Other US- and China-focused REITs in Singapore recently reported earnings, but didn&#39;t conduct external valuations for their properties for their midyear disclosures. Many vehicles do that only for their full-year results.</p><p> Write to Weilun Soon at <a href="mailto:weilun.soon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">weilun.soon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-office-woes-and-chinas-slowdown-rattle-singapores-reit-market-e1367051</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-office-woes-and-chinas-slowdown-rattle-singapores-reit-market-e1367051<author><![CDATA[Weilun Soon]]></author><category> wsjfinance-asia</category><category> commercial re</category><category> Trusts/Funds/Financial Vehicles</category><category> Investment Trusts</category><category> Real Estate Investment Trusts</category><category> Insurance</category><category> Life Insurance</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>金融服务</category><category>Investing/Securities</category><category> Residential REITs</category><category>房地产</category><category>Retail REITs</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Commercial RE</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Dasin Retail Trust</category><category> CEDU.SG</category><category> SG:CEDU</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>trusts</category><category> funds</category><category> financial vehicles</category><category> investment trusts</category><category> real estate investment trusts</category><category>保险</category><category>人寿保险</category><category>房地产</category><category>建造</category><category>financial services</category><category> investing</category><category> securities</category><category> residential reits</category><category> retail reits</category></item></channel></rss>